The patterns that get Angular code rejected every time — with the wrong code, the right code, and why the difference matters once the application hits production.

Code review is one of the most important things a senior developer does — and one of the most difficult to do well. A lazy code review catches syntax errors. A good code review catches design problems. An excellent code review teaches the author something they did not know they needed to learn.
Over 14 years of Angular development, I have reviewed hundreds of pull requests across enterprise banking platforms, fintech dashboards, healthcare portals, and internal tooling applications. I have seen the same patterns rejected again and again — not because the code does not work, but because it works until it does not.
This article is the collection of patterns I reject most consistently, with the wrong code, the right code, and the production failure that the wrong code is heading toward.

Rejection Pattern 1 — Unmanaged Subscriptions
This is the most common rejection comment I write. A component subscribes to an Observable in ngOnInit and never cleans up. The component is destroyed. The subscription continues. Memory grows. After two hours of heavy navigation, the application slows and then behaves strangely.
// ❌ Rejected every time
@Component({ changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush })
export class UserDashboardComponent implements OnInit {
users: User[] = []; ngOnInit() {
this.userService.getActiveUsers().subscribe(users => {
this.users = users; // Subscription never cleaned up
});
}
}The subscribe call here has no cleanup. Every time this component is mounted and unmounted — which in a single-page application with active navigation can happen dozens of times per session — a new subscription is added. None of them are ever removed.
// ✅ Approved — toSignal() handles everything
@Component({ changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush })
export class UserDashboardComponent {
// No ngOnInit. No subscription. No cleanup needed.
users = toSignal(this.userService.getActiveUsers(), { initialValue: [] }); constructor(private userService: UserService) {}
}toSignal() subscribes once, cleans up automatically when the component is destroyed, and the template reads it as a Signal. If the Observable is for a one-time HTTP request, toSignal() is the cleanest modern pattern. If you need the Observable for ongoing side effects, use takeUntilDestroyed():
// ✅ Also approved — takeUntilDestroyed for ongoing streams
constructor(private notificationService: NotificationService) {
this.notificationService.stream$
.pipe(takeUntilDestroyed())
.subscribe(notification => this.handle(notification));
}The production failure this prevents: In a real-time dashboard application I reviewed, a WebSocket-driven component was mounted and unmounted every time the user switched between tabs. After 40 minutes of use, there were 23 simultaneous WebSocket subscriptions all updating the same UI. The component would flash and flicker as 23 parallel subscriptions raced to update the same signal. The fix was two lines.

Rejection Pattern 2 — any Type Annotations
TypeScript’s primary value proposition is compile-time type safety. Every any annotation is a deliberate opt-out from that safety net. In a code review, I treat any the same way I would treat a // TODO: fix this later comment with no ticket number — it is technical debt with no payment plan.
// ❌ Rejected
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class ProductService {
constructor(private http: HttpClient) {} getProducts(): any { // any return type
return this.http.get('/api/products');
} processResponse(response: any) { // any parameter
return response.data.items; // TypeScript cannot catch a typo here
}
}// ✅ Approved
export interface Product {
id: number;
name: string;
price: number;
category: string;
inStock: boolean;
}export interface ApiResponse<T> {
data: { items: T[] };
total: number;
}@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class ProductService {
constructor(private http: HttpClient) {} getProducts(): Observable<Product[]> {
return this.http.get<ApiResponse<Product>>('/api/products').pipe(
map(response => response.data.items) // TypeScript knows exactly what this is
);
}
}The additional lines are not ceremony — they are documentation with teeth. If the API changes and response.data.items becomes response.items, TypeScript catches it at compile time instead of in production at 2 AM.
The production failure this prevents: A team I worked with had a service that returned any. The API team renamed a field from userId to user_id in a response. The Angular application continued to compile without a single error. The bug showed up six weeks later in a rarely-used report page. The fix took 45 minutes. Finding it took two days.

Rejection Pattern 3 — Complex Logic in Templates
Templates are for presentation. Any logic that involves conditions, calculations, or data transformations belongs in the component or service, not the template. When I see a complex expression in a template, I leave one comment: “This belongs in a computed() or a method.”
<!-- ❌ Rejected — template is doing too much work -->
<div class="dashboard-panel"
*ngIf="user && user.role === 'admin' &&
user.permissions.includes('view-reports') &&
!user.isSuspended &&
featureFlags.reportsEnabled &&
(dateRange.from | date) !== (dateRange.to | date)">
<app-reports-panel />
</div><span class="total">
{{ (orders | filter:'status':'completed').length > 0
? ((orders | filter:'status':'completed') | sum:'amount' | currency:'INR')
: 'No completed orders' }}
</span>// ✅ Approved — logic in component, template stays clean@Component({ changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush })
export class DashboardComponent {
private user = inject(UserStore).currentUser;
private featureFlags = inject(FeatureFlagService).flags;
orders = input<Order[]>([]); // Named, testable, readable
canViewReports = computed(() => {
const u = this.user();
return u !== null
&& u.role === 'admin'
&& u.permissions.includes('view-reports')
&& !u.isSuspended
&& this.featureFlags().reportsEnabled;
}); completedOrdersTotal = computed(() => {
const completed = this.orders().filter(o => o.status === 'completed');
if (completed.length === 0) return 'No completed orders';
const total = completed.reduce((sum, o) => sum + o.amount, 0);
return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-IN', { style: 'currency', currency: 'INR' }).format(total);
});
}<!-- ✅ Template is now just presentation -->
@if (canViewReports()) {
<app-reports-panel />
}
<span class="total">{{ completedOrdersTotal() }}</span>Two additional benefits: canViewReports and completedOrdersTotal are now trivially unit-testable. You do not need to render a component to verify the logic — you call the computed value and assert the result.

Rejection Pattern 4 — Missing trackBy on Lists
Every @for loop that renders a list of objects should have a track expression that identifies each item uniquely. Without it, Angular cannot determine which items changed when the list updates — it destroys and recreates all DOM nodes every time the array reference changes.
<!-- ❌ Rejected — no track expression -->
@for (product of products(); track product) {
<app-product-card [product]="product" />
}<!-- Also rejected — tracking by index is almost always wrong -->
@for (product of products(); track $index) {
<app-product-card [product]="product" />
}<!-- ✅ Approved — track by stable unique identifier -->
@for (product of products(); track product.id) {
<app-product-card [product]="product" />
}Tracking by index is wrong because if an item is removed from the middle of the list, every component after the removed item gets the wrong index. Angular sees them as changed and re-renders all of them, destroying and recreating DOM nodes, losing any local state those components held (expanded state, scroll position, partially filled forms).
The production failure this prevents: A product listing page was re-rendering 200+ cards every time a single filter was applied — because the track was missing and Angular recreated all 200 DOM nodes with every update. Adding track product.id reduced re-render time from 340ms to under 20ms on the same device.

Rejection Pattern 5 — Direct DOM Manipulation
Angular manages the DOM. When you bypass Angular’s rendering and manipulate the DOM directly with document.querySelector or ElementRef.nativeElement, you create a hidden dependency between your code and the DOM structure that Angular is not aware of. This breaks server-side rendering, Web Workers, and any future renderer optimisation Angular might introduce.
// ❌ Rejected
@Component({})
export class ChartComponent implements AfterViewInit {
ngAfterViewInit() {
// Direct DOM manipulation bypasses Angular
const canvas = document.querySelector('#chart-canvas') as HTMLCanvasElement;
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
new Chart(ctx, this.chartConfig); // Also rejected
this.elementRef.nativeElement.querySelector('.legend').style.display = 'none';
}
}// ✅ Approved — ViewChild + Angular Renderer2
@Component({
template: `<canvas #chartCanvas></canvas>`
})
export class ChartComponent implements AfterViewInit {
@ViewChild('chartCanvas') private canvasRef!: ElementRef<HTMLCanvasElement>;
private renderer = inject(Renderer2); ngAfterViewInit() {
// ViewChild — Angular knows about this reference
const ctx = this.canvasRef.nativeElement.getContext('2d');
new Chart(ctx!, this.chartConfig);
} hideLegend() {
// Renderer2 — SSR-compatible, renderer-agnostic
this.renderer.setStyle(this.legendEl.nativeElement, 'display', 'none');
}
}For showing/hiding elements, the Angular-native approach is almost always preferable to style manipulation:
<!-- ✅ Best — let Angular manage visibility -->
@if (showLegend()) {
<div class="legend">...</div>
}
Rejection Pattern 6 — Barrel File Abuse
Barrel files (index.ts) are useful for defining the public API of a feature module. They become a problem when they are used to re-export everything indiscriminately, creating deep import chains that slow down the TypeScript compiler and make circular dependency analysis impossible.
// ❌ Rejected — barrel file that re-exports everything
// features/users/index.ts
export * from './components/user-list.component';
export * from './components/user-detail.component';
export * from './components/user-form.component';
export * from './services/user.service';
export * from './services/user-api.service';
export * from './services/user-cache.service';
export * from './models/user.model';
export * from './models/user-role.model';
export * from './guards/user.guard';
export * from './store/user.store';
// 40 more exports...// ✅ Approved — barrel file exposes only the public API
// features/users/index.ts
// Only what OTHER features need — not every internal implementation
export { UserListComponent } from './components/user-list.component';
export { UserDetailComponent } from './components/user-detail.component';
export type { User, UserRole } from './models/user.model';
// Internal services, guards, and stores are NOT exported
// — consumers should not depend on internal implementation detailsThe rule is: a barrel file’s exports define the feature’s contract. If another feature needs to import an internal service directly, that is a signal the architecture has a boundary violation — not a reason to add the export.

Rejection Pattern 7 — HTTP Calls Inside Components
Components render UI. Services fetch data. When an HTTP call lives inside a component, it becomes impossible to cache, difficult to test, and impossible to share with other components that need the same data.
// ❌ Rejected
@Component({})
export class OrderListComponent implements OnInit {
orders: Order[] = []; constructor(private http: HttpClient) {} // HttpClient injected directly ngOnInit() {
this.http.get
